        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Synthetic media</strong> is content — audio, video, images, or text — that is entirely generated or substantially manipulated by artificial intelligence rather than recorded or created by human hands. It spans AI-generated images from Midjourney or DALL-E, AI voiceovers, deepfake video, AI avatar presenters, and AI-written text. In marketing, synthetic media enables scale and personalisation that was previously impossible. It also demands clearer ethical frameworks and disclosure practices than any previous content technology.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">AI and Emerging</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">AI-Generated Media, Generative Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">9 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Synthetic media is no longer a futuristic concern — it is the present reality of content production. Millions of pieces of AI-generated content are published daily across social media, advertising platforms, news sites, and ecommerce catalogues. Understanding what synthetic media is, where it's legitimate, and where it creates risk is now a core competency for marketers, SEO professionals, and content creators.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is synthetic media?</h2>
        <p>The term "synthetic media" emerged to describe content where AI is the primary author, generator, or manipulator — as distinct from content where AI assists a human creator. The key characteristic is generation at scale from learned models, rather than direct human creation or conventional digital tools.</p>
        <p>Synthetic media encompasses several distinct content types:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>AI-generated images:</strong> Images created from text prompts by diffusion models (Midjourney, DALL-E 3, Stable Diffusion, Firefly). The image has no physical-world original — it is generated entirely from pattern recognition in the model's training data.</li>
          <li><strong>Deepfake video:</strong> Video that places a real person's likeness into footage they were not part of, or generates entirely synthetic video of realistic people.</li>
          <li><strong>AI voiceovers and voice clones:</strong> AI-generated speech that mimics a real person's voice (with or without their consent) or generates synthetic voices with no human original.</li>
          <li><strong>AI avatar presenters:</strong> Synthetic video presenters — lifelike animated characters or virtual humans — generated from prompts or templates. Platforms like HeyGen and Synthesia produce these at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>AI-generated text:</strong> Written content generated by large language models (GPT-4, Claude, Gemini). Includes articles, product descriptions, ad copy, email templates, and social posts.</li>
          <li><strong>AI-generated music and audio:</strong> Music, sound effects, and audio tracks generated by AI without human composition.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="marketing-uses">Legitimate marketing uses of synthetic media</h2>
        <p>Synthetic media has unlocked capabilities that would have required prohibitive budgets using conventional production methods. These use cases are widespread and increasingly mainstream:</p>

        <h3>Video localisation at scale</h3>
        <p>AI dubbing and lip-sync technology allows a single video to be translated and localised into dozens of languages with an AI-generated voice that matches the original speaker's tone and timing. Netflix and major brands use this for global content distribution without reshooting.</p>

        <h3>Personalised video marketing</h3>
        <p>Platforms like Tavus generate personalised video messages at scale — where an AI model speaks each recipient's name and references their specific context, appearing as a custom recording from a presenter or executive. Used in outbound sales and account-based marketing.</p>

        <h3>Ecommerce product imagery</h3>
        <p>AI-generated product images remove the need for traditional photo shoots. Fashion brands generate product-on-model imagery at scale, home decor brands create lifestyle context images, and ecommerce businesses generate colour and variant imagery without physical samples.</p>

        <h3>Ad creative generation and testing</h3>
        <p>Synthetic media tools generate hundreds of ad creative variants from a single brief — different backgrounds, models, colour schemes, and copy combinations. This enables creative A/B testing at a scale not achievable with human design teams.</p>

        <h3>Training data and simulation</h3>
        <p>Companies generate synthetic media to train their own AI models or create simulation environments — without the privacy concerns and costs of capturing real-world data at scale.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Market size</div>
          <p>The synthetic media market was estimated at $3.1 billion in 2025 and is projected to exceed $11 billion by 2028, driven by AI image generation, AI video production tools, and enterprise adoption of AI avatar platforms (MarketsandMarkets, 2025).</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="seo-implications">Synthetic media and SEO — what Google's position means for publishers</h2>
        <p>Google's Helpful Content System does not prohibit AI-generated content. Its 2023 and 2024 updates explicitly stated that the question is whether content is helpful, not whether it was written by a human or AI. However, several specific synthetic media uses do create SEO risk:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mass-generated thin content.</strong> Using AI to generate thousands of pages with minimal human review or value-add is exactly what the Helpful Content System targets. The origin being AI is not the issue — the quality being thin is.</li>
          <li><strong>AI-generated images passed as real photography.</strong> If product images, location images, or person photos are AI-generated but presented as authentic, this is a trust issue with users that can drive high bounce rates and poor user signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Fake reviews and testimonials.</strong> AI-generated review content is explicitly prohibited by Google's policies and actively detected. Reviews and testimonials must reflect genuine experiences.</li>
          <li><strong>AI-generated author identities.</strong> Synthetic author bios with AI-generated headshots and invented credentials undermine E-E-A-T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness) signals that are increasingly important for content quality assessment.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="deepfakes">Deepfakes — the highest-risk category</h2>
        <p>Deepfakes represent the most ethically fraught category of synthetic media. The ability to generate realistic video of real people saying or doing things they did not say or do creates risks that extend far beyond marketing:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Non-consensual intimate imagery (a criminal offence in growing number of jurisdictions)</li>
          <li>Disinformation and political manipulation</li>
          <li>CEO fraud and financial scams</li>
          <li>Reputational damage to public figures and private individuals</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For marketers, deepfake risks include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Using a celebrity or influencer's likeness without consent in advertising</li>
          <li>Generating fake customer testimonials with realistic video</li>
          <li>Impersonating executives or brand representatives</li>
          <li>Using competitor executives' likenesses in comparison advertising</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="disclosure-regulations">Disclosure requirements and regulations</h2>
        <p>Regulation of synthetic media is developing rapidly. Key frameworks as of mid-2026:</p>

        <h3>EU AI Act (effective 2025)</h3>
        <p>Requires disclosure when AI has generated or manipulated content depicting real people in video or audio. Applies to advertising, social media content, news, and entertainment. Non-compliance can result in fines up to 3% of global annual revenue.</p>

        <h3>FTC (United States)</h3>
        <p>The FTC's updated endorsement guidelines (2023) require disclosure when AI manipulation materially alters a human endorser's appearance or voice. The FTC has also signalled enforcement interest in AI-generated testimonials and fake reviews.</p>

        <h3>UK ASA</h3>
        <p>The Advertising Standards Authority requires ads to be clearly identifiable. AI-generated advertising content that mimics organic content or real people must carry appropriate disclosure. The CAP Code applies regardless of the production method.</p>

        <h3>Platform-specific rules</h3>
        <p>Meta, TikTok, YouTube, and X have implemented AI content labelling requirements for AI-generated or AI-manipulated content. Platforms automatically detect and label some AI content and require creator disclosure for the rest. Failure to disclose can result in content removal or account suspension.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Marketing risk</div>
          <p>Using AI-generated images of real people, AI-generated celebrity endorsements, or AI voice clones of individuals without explicit consent is both an ethical violation and a legal liability in most jurisdictions. The speed at which this content can be produced does not reduce the legal exposure — it may increase it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for ethical synthetic media use in marketing</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Disclose AI generation where material.</strong> If your ad video uses an AI presenter, your product image is AI-generated, or your testimonial is synthesised, disclose it. Consumer trust research consistently shows that transparency about AI use does not significantly reduce ad effectiveness — but discovered non-disclosure does.</li>
          <li><strong>Never use real people's likenesses without consent.</strong> This includes celebrities, competitors, influencers, and private individuals. Consent must be explicit, in writing, and for the specific use case.</li>
          <li><strong>Apply human review to all AI-generated content.</strong> AI generation without editorial review produces errors, hallucinations, and quality inconsistencies that damage brand trust. Human review is not optional — it's the step that makes synthetic media legitimate.</li>
          <li><strong>Maintain authentic author and creator identity.</strong> Don't create synthetic author personas. AI-generated content should be attributed to real humans who reviewed and are accountable for it, or clearly labelled as AI-generated with no attributed human author.</li>
          <li><strong>Build internal AI content policies before scaling.</strong> Define which use cases are approved, what disclosure standards apply, and how quality review works before deploying synthetic media at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>Track and audit AI-generated content.</strong> Keep records of what was AI-generated and when, for compliance, brand audit, and quality management purposes.</li>
        </ol>

